The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 Washington, Dec. 28: Enron Corp?s former chief accountant, Richard A. Causey, has agreed to plead guilty to criminal conduct that preceded the energy company?s collapse into bankruptcy. This will give prosecutors another key witness against former chief executives Kenneth L. Lay and Jeffrey K. Skilling. Causey, who is facing more than 24 criminal charges, is scheduled to appear in a Houston court today, according to court records.

 New Delhi, Dec. 28: Bharat Sanchar Nigam and Mahanagar Telephone Nigam are likely to finalise the proposed joint venture company for setting up a submarine cable link before March. Sources said it would be a 50:50 venture between the two public sector firms.

 Calcutta, Dec. 28: Allahabad Bank will soon select the vendor for its core banking solution (CBS). The bank had appointed Ernst amp; Young to implement the CBS.

 New Delhi, Dec. 28: To rope in talents available outside for running public sector companies, the government is considering making the selection of functional directors and chairmen more open.

 Mumbai, Dec. 28: The Bombay Stock Exchange today asked all listed companies to comply with the amended Clause 49 of the listing agreement with effect from January 1.




